    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1930-10-02T06:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1930-10-02T06:00:00-05:00" n="587"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d587">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">393.1121 Wong Bock Yue/28: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in China</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Johnson</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Peiping</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1930-10-02T19:00:00+08:00"
                            >October 2, 1930—7 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received October 4—9:30 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>874. Reference Department’s mail instruction No. 199, August 6 [<hi rend="italic"
                        >4</hi>], 1930.<note n="28" xml:id="d587fn1">Not printed.</note>
                </p>
                <list>
                    <label>1.</label>
                    <item>Wong Bock Yue, who was released shortly after the turnover of Peiping,
                        called at the Legation today to thank the Legation for its efforts in his
                        behalf. He has promised to give the Legation a detailed account of his
                        arrest, imprisonment, and release which will be forwarded to the Department
                        by mail when received.<note n="28" xml:id="d587fn2">Not printed.</note>
                    </item>
                    <label>2.</label>
                    <item>He stated that his arrest and imprisonment were for editorials written by
                        him displeasing to the Left Wing; that he was never brought to trial and was
                        never given an opportunity to procure evidence to rebut the charges brought
                        against him. He was, however, well treated.</item>
                </list>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Johnson</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
